In JavaScript, the `document` object is used to access the current page of the application. To define the `document`, you can use the following syntax:
```javascript
const document = window.document
```
The `document` object has a property called `window` that represents the global object.

You can also define variables or objects within the `document` object, but it is not recommended to define variables or objects that will be used by multiple pages or applications.

It's also recommended to include the `window` object in your code, so that it can be accessed from any page.
```
const myObject = {
  someProperty: 'some value',
  setSomeProperty: () => {
    this.someProperty = 'new value';
  },
  getSomeProperty: () => {
    return this.someProperty;
  }
}
```
In this example, `myObject` is a simple object with properties `someProperty` and `setSomeProperty`, and it has a method `getSomeProperty` that returns the value of `this.someProperty`.

You can also define functions and use them in the `document`, so that you can access the global object from any page.
```
const addNumbers = (x, y) => {
  return x + y;
};

const document = window.document;
const myVar = document.getElementById('my-input-id');
